	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=103498><span id=Sage>kdsktan</span></a><br><b><span id=Sage>Sage</span></b><br><span id=notbold>129 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [5.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>I was bored one day and wrote a rough guide for warriors for my guild class site. Anyway, I thought id post it here for some of those newer to the class to learn a couple of tricks i myself have learnt. Also, the guide is aimed more at the 50+ level so pls bear that in mind.<br><br>First, everyone has heard this before, but the cornerstone for all our actions is the fact that as a warrior, we have 2 primary roles. First, to be the main point of contact with the mob to soak up the damage and second, to do what damage we can. <br> <br>A lot of people make the assumption that its just a case of target, autoattack, taunt, slam/kick, rinse and repeat. To me, it's a lot more than that. <br> <br>So, what more is there to this apart from this?&nbsp;&nbsp;<br> <br>Pulling <br>Sure, monks and SKs have it over us on pulling because of FD. But that doesn't mean we can't pull and on occassions when there is no monk or SK, then we have no choice but to pull.  <br>Ok first thing. Don't start pulling in a zone that is new to you. There are a lot of variables to pulling which you will only appreciate once you get to know the zone a little aggro radius, pathing etc. Watch and learn as best you can first. For instance, in places like PoI, I have learnt that it can be easier to get single pulls by walking up to a mob and getting just within its aggro radius than to bow pull it, as the pathing is a little bit different for each. <br> <br>On the subject of bow pulling, this is definitely the recommended method for most types of pulls. There is no excuse for you, at this level, not to have at least a 150 range bow and if possible, there are 190/200 range bows which you can get. There is also no excuse not to have a ready supply of arrows.  Always plan ahead, if you know you are going to do a long day of exp grinding, go to town and stock up. I will always go and buy/make as many arrows as I can as you will be surprised how much you get through in a days session. <br> <br>Never rush a bow pull. In places like PoN, mobs can spawn in the way of your intended target, or with weird pathing you can get adds before you know it. So, take your time, pick your target, watch it for a couple of secs and when your sure its clear, tag it. If there are mobs in the vicinity, wait for them to clear before you do anything. When the mob is tagged, don't just turn and run. Wait for the mob to get close to make sure you haven't picked up any adds. Then run back to camp. Just before you get back to camp, check again that there are no adds. Usually, you will also have the opportunity to shoot again just to pick up a little more aggro. <br> <br>In the case of multiple adds you have to make a decision there and then what to do. If you have an ench and are confident in the group, then by all means take them back. If you are not sure, don't be a hero, your group won' thank you for a  CR. Stand there and take it like a man. <br> <br>One final point. There are range slot items which have better stats than bows. Hotkey the bow when it is in the range slot and the range item when it is in an open inventory slot (not in a bag). Drag both to your hotkey box. That way, when you pull you have your bow equipped. As you are running back to camp, by pressing the hotkeyed items you can swop out with a range slot item without opening your inventory. <br> <br>Multiple mobs <br>This is a bit of a follow on from the previous point. If you know you have to do a pull where you will definitely get one or more adds, then a bit of planning will go a long way. If there is a rooter / enchanter in the group, ask them to come up to you so they can root/mez one whilst you grab the other. <br> <br>Never forget to help your enchanter as much as possible. Sure, they could mez 4 mobs which are right on top of each other, but it makes life easy for them and for you if the mobs are all spaced apart. So, if you have say 3 mobs on you or you know you will get multiple adds, tell the ench. Pull the mobs and stop away from camp. Let the ench mez one. Then run back a little bit more, stop again. Mez second. Then bring the third one back in. Where you have adds in camp, you can still do the same thing by doing a circular route within the camp whilst the ench mezzes the rest. . <br> <br>As a general rule, melee mobs get killed first, casters second. <br> <br>Aggro Management <br> <br>Pallys and SKs will always have the jump on us re aggro. So will reckless rangers and rogues and monks and most everyone else! <br> <br>There are things you can do though to make sure you keep aggro as much as possible. First, if you are grouped with people with high haste items, then equip your haste item. Alternatively, ask them to swop out if possible to a slower item. Don't be shy to ask to be allowed to tank a mob for a few secs as well to gain aggro. Pride just ends up getting you and everyone killed. <br> <br>The most important thing is of course your weapons. I used to use a combo of 1 handed weps but now find that I can hold aggro just as well with my Narandis lance. I think the same goes for a few other 2 handers currently out there. I would advise that you save up and buy at least 1 weapon with a reasonable aggro proc. For gulug, he has a number of proccing weapons- wavecrasher (slow + dot), silken whip of ensnaring (snare), frostbringer (Ac debuff &amp; DD)  &amp; Narandis lance (500 dmg dot). If you are going to use proccing weapons, try and get your unbuffed dex to above 100 as a general rule. Normally, you will find that you use 2 primary 1handed weapons and a 2 handed weapon. What I do is have keep inventory slots open and I hotkey all these 3 weapons. That way, during the course of a fight I can swop out the weapons as required. In a situation where I really need to get aggro (and this is good practice to follow), as soon as a weapon procs swop it out with another one. Assuming they all proc, I can keep a AC debuff, 2 dots, snare and a slow on a mob. You can imagine that that gains aggro reasonably well. So, don't be single minded about your weapons. Variety is the spice of life after all. <br> <br>Taunt. Taunt as best you can to get aggro. Once you have it, don't keep taunt pressed. You will never know when the mob aggroes a caster and you need the taunt button to be refreshed. <br> <br>Also, it helps to keep as close as possible to a mob. So much so that you may not even see him  without looking down. <br> <br>Shield Disc <br> <br>Love it. Gives me something more to do and adds a bit more variety to a warriors repertoire. I basically have 3 hotkeys for shield. A simple /shield %T and 2 additional hotkeys which I make everytime I group. Eg if I group with enchanter X and cleric Y, then I will make hotkey /shield X and /shield Y. That way, if they get aggroed, you don't have to target them.  <br>Shield works best if they are standing right beside you and the mob is in front of both of you. So make sure you tell them that if they get aggro not to run around but to stick close to you or at least stand still so you can run up to them. <br> <br>Don't forget, it recycles every 3 mins, so you can more or less use it for each pull. So don't be scared to hit that hotkey at even the slightest hint of aggro on a caster.  <br> <br>General Melee <br> <br>If there is no rogue in your group, make sure that you stay in front of the mob and tell all the other melees to get to the back of the mob. Theres less AC at the back so they do more damage. Its really wasteful to have 2/3 melees all hitting the front of a mob. <br> <br>Pets - pets are not clever and won't always know to get to the back of a mob. So, you have to do it for them by positioning the mob accordingly. Also, don't forget that Mages have BS pets so this is especially important. Another reason is that in PoP, mobs rampage/enrage so if you don't keep the pet behind the mob they tend to die, then the sham/mage/necro etc will not like you as they have to waste mana to recast. <br> <br>Slam/Kick. Kick caps out before slam, so always practice slam more than kick, even though it may do less dmg. Remember, your not there for dmg. To prevent spam, make sure you set up a couple of windows for casting messages etc. For casting mobs, look out for casting message before you slam. Don't waste slams unnecessarily, especially where there are CH mobs. <br> <br>Most people will say that warriors tend to have an easier job than some other classes. To some extent, thats probably true. Therefore, there is no excuse for taking your eye off the ball during a fight. You have to be aware of exactly what is going on around you. If it helps, turn the mob with your back to a wall so you can see better. Position the casters in as safe a spot as possible. In addition to a general /inc %T hotkey, I also have a hotkey to say help me kill %t or something like that. This is useful when you switch out mobs during an accidental mez, or when you have a bunch of mobs grouped together and you are killing them one by one, as not everytime do people use the assist key. <br> <br> <br>Ok thats about all I can remember for today. Im adding to this and thinking of a raid MA guide so will post here when they are done.<br> <br>Gulug <br>60 Warlord<br> <br><br></p>&nbsp;<br> </td></td></tr>
